        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1962-03-21T18:23:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1962-03-21T18:23:00-05:00" n="108"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d108">
                <head>108. <gloss target="#t_Tosec_1">Tosec</gloss> 103 to Geneva, March 21<note
                        n="1" type="source" xml:id="d108fn1">Instructions to <persName
                            corresp="#p_RD_1">Rusk</persName>/<persName corresp="#p_HAFD_1"
                            >Home</persName> on getting <persName corresp="#p_GAA_1"
                            >Gromyko</persName> rejection of international verification of test ban
                        treaty on public record. Secret. 1 p. Department of State, Central Files,
                        700.5611/3–2162.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1962-03-21T18:23:00-05:00">March 21, 1962, 6:23 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <pb facs="d108-1" n="1" type="facsimile" xml:id="d108-1"/>
                <p>For Secretary from Acting Secretary. Before you leave Geneva, President desires
                    that you and <persName corresp="#p_HAFD_1">Home</persName> attempt get <persName
                        corresp="#p_GAA_1">Gromyko</persName> on public record as categorically
                    rejecting international verification for nuclear test ban treaty. Would suggest
                    this might be done by referring to previous <persName corresp="#p_TSK_1"
                        >Tsarapkin</persName> statements to effect Soviets will not accept
                    international verification and express hope that <persName corresp="#p_TSK_1"
                        >Tsarapkin</persName>’s position does not reflect official position of
                    Soviet government. You might, in simplest terms, describe key element in US
                    position as being requirement objective international system to verify that ban
                    against testing is being observed. US will not settle for less and will consider
                    any proposal which offers effective international verification.</p>
                <p>We note you tentatively planning Thursday speech on nuclear tests. Would suggest
                    you give speech at that time in order allow time <persName corresp="#p_GAA_1"
                        >Gromyko</persName> reaction before you leave.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed corresp="#p_BGW_1">
                        <persName corresp="#p_BGW_1">Ball</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
